There‚Äôs a ritual that happens every September. Apple unveils its latest iPhone, and millions of us suddenly discover that the device in our pocket‚Äîthe one we loved just yesterday‚Äîhas become obsolete.
It‚Äôs marketing genius, really. The same phone that was ‚Äúrevolutionary‚Äù twelve months ago is now just‚Ä¶old.
Big tech companies have mastered the art of manufactured desire. Apple and Samsung don‚Äôt need to release a new phone every year‚Äîthe technological leaps between generations have become increasingly small. But why wait three years when you can extract revenue annually?

Title: rv, a new kind of Ruby management tool
Description: For the last ten years or so of working on Bundler, I‚Äôve had a wish rattling around: I want a better dependency manager. It doesn‚Äôt just manage your gems, it manages your ruby versions, too. It doesn‚Äôt just manage your ruby versions, it installs pre-compiled rubies so you don‚Äôt have to wait for ruby to compile from source every time. And more than all of that, it makes it completely trivial to run any script or tool written in ruby, even if that script or tool needs a different ruby than your application does.

Title: When Switches Flood LLDP Traffic ¬´ ipSpace.net blog
Description:
A networking engineer (let‚Äôs call him Joe1) sent me an interesting challenge: they built a data center network with Cisco switches, and the switches flood LLDP packets between servers.
That would be interesting by itself (the whole network would appear as a single hub), but they‚Äôre also using DCBX (which is riding in LLDP TLVs), and the DCBX parameters are negotiated between servers (not between servers and adjacent switches), sometimes resulting in NIC resets2.
